  <div class="page-content">
    <div class="hero"><h1>What is a Colposcopy?</h1><p>What to expect during the procedure, biopsy details, and interpreting results.</p></div>

        <h2>The Colposcopy Procedure Explained</h2>
        <p>A colposcopy is a diagnostic procedure used to closely examine the cervix, vagina, and vulva for signs of disease. It is most commonly recommended when a patient has received an abnormal <a href="/sites/hpv-research/what-is-pap-smear">Pap smear</a> result or tested positive for high-risk HPV. The procedure allows the healthcare provider to visually identify areas of <a href="/sites/hpv-research/what-is-cervical-dysplasia">cervical dysplasia</a> and take targeted biopsies for precise histological diagnosis.</p>

        <h3>Why is it Performed?</h3>
        <p>While cytology (Pap smears) screens for abnormal cells that have shed from the cervix, colposcopy evaluates the actual tissue architecture. It is crucial for determining the extent and severity of any abnormalities, guiding subsequent clinical management.</p>

        <h3>What to Expect During the Procedure</h3>
        <p>The procedure is similar to a routine pelvic exam and typically takes 10 to 20 minutes in an outpatient setting:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>A speculum is inserted to open the vaginal walls.</li>
            <li>The colposcope, a specialized magnifying instrument, is positioned just outside the vagina. It does not enter the body.</li>
            <li>A mild acetic acid (vinegar) solution is applied to the cervix. This solution causes abnormal cells to turn white (acetowhite lesions), making them easier to identify.</li>
            <li>A special filter or light may be used to examine the vascular patterns (blood vessels) on the cervix, as abnormal vascularization can be a sign of high-grade dysplasia or early cancer.</li>
        </ul>

        <h3>The Biopsy Process</h3>
        <p>If the provider identifies suspicious areas, they will take a small tissue sample (biopsy) using a specialized instrument. They may also perform an endocervical curettage (ECC) to sample cells from the cervical canal, which cannot be seen directly. The biopsy process may cause a brief pinch or cramping sensation. A topical solution, such as Monsel's solution, is often applied afterward to stop any minor bleeding.</p>

        <h3>Interpreting the Results</h3>
        <p>The biopsy samples are sent to a pathology lab where they are analyzed and graded using the Cervical Intraepithelial Neoplasia (CIN) system. Based on whether the results show CIN 1, CIN 2, or CIN 3, the clinician will recommend continued observation or a treatment procedure like <a href="/sites/hpv-research/what-is-leep-procedure">LEEP</a>.</p>


    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="faq-section">

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-header">Does a colposcopy hurt?</h3>
            <div class="faq-content">
                <p>Most patients experience only mild discomfort, similar to a routine Pap smear. If a biopsy is taken, you may feel a brief pinch and some menstrual-like cramping.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-header">How long does it take to get colposcopy results?</h3>
            <div class="faq-content">
                <p>Biopsy results typically take 1 to 2 weeks to be processed by the pathology lab and returned to your healthcare provider.</p>
            </div>
        </div>

        <div class="faq-item">
            <h3 class="faq-header">Can I have a colposcopy while menstruating?</h3>
            <div class="faq-content">
                <p>It is generally recommended to schedule a colposcopy when you are not menstruating, as heavy bleeding can obscure the provider's view of the cervix. However, light spotting is usually acceptable.</p>
            </div>
        </div>
        </div>
